# Architecture-First Robustness (Wee)

## Decision Standard

- Before coding, identify the existing system that already owns the concern (store slice, shared hook, motion factory, UI primitive, persistence path).
- Prefer extending that system over adding parallel state, one-off logic, or duplicated behavior.
- For legacy behavior changes, fix root causes in shared layers so future features inherit the fix automatically.

## Anti-Drift Rules

- Do not introduce ad hoc fallbacks that bypass canonical contracts (`useConsolidatedAppStore`, `appearanceBySpace`, unified settings persistence, shared motion tokens/variants).
- Avoid feature-local constants when an existing token/config domain exists; promote reusable tokens/config instead.
- Keep one source of truth for each domain (state, persistence, animation lifecycle, UI styling).

## Performance + Scalability

- Design for long-running Electron sessions: minimize churn, avoid unnecessary subscriptions/re-renders, and debounce/batch persistence or expensive work.
- Reuse memoized selectors and shared hooks before creating new reactive pathways.
- Prefer predictable lifecycle-safe flows (mount/animate/unmount, persist/flush/reload) over opportunistic patching.

## Required Validation

- Verify both behavior and architecture: ensure the change works and does not create a parallel subsystem.
- For settings or appearance changes, verify restart persistence behavior.
- For animation/motion changes, verify rapid interaction paths (toggle/switch/select repeatedly) without visual regressions.
